# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: charlie-knepper
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:charlie-knepper/1899-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1899 throughout the world.
[src:charlie-knepper/1899-in-baseball] Buck Freeman of the Washington Senators leads all batters with 25 home runs during the regular season, more than double hit by Bobby Wallace of the St.
[src:charlie-knepper/1899-in-baseball] Louis Perfectos, who finished with 12 homers.
[src:charlie-knepper/1899-in-baseball] Freeman's tally was not surpassed until 1919, when Babe Ruth belted 29 home runs for the Boston Red Sox.
[src:charlie-knepper/1899-in-baseball] The National League would remain at eight teams until 1962.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Prior to the organization of Madison County, William Conner entered the land upon which Anderson is located.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Conner later sold the ground to John and Sarah Berry, who donated 32 acres (13 ha) of their land to Madison County on the condition that the county seat be moved from Pendleton to Anderson.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] John Berry laid out the first plat of Anderson on November 7, 1827.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] In 1828 the seat of justice was moved from Pendleton to Anderson.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The city is named for Chief William "Adam" Anderson, whose mother was Lenape and whose father was of Swedish descent.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Chief Anderson's name in Lenape was *Kikthawenund*, meaning "creaking boughs".
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The Lenape village was known as "Anderson's Town", though the Moravian missionaries called it "The Heathen Town Four Miles Away".
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Anderson was also known as "Andersonton" before being formally organized as Anderson.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Introduction of internal improvements by the Mammoth Internal Improvement Act caused a growth in the population in 1837.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] In December 1838, Anderson was incorporated as a town with 350 inhabitants.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The Central Canal, a branch of the Wabash and Erie Canal, was planned to come through Anderson.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Work continued on the canal during 1838 and the beginning of 1839, but the work was soon suspended by the state following effects of the Panic of 1837.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The town again became a sleepy village until 1849, when it was incorporated a second time as a town.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Many new commercial ventures located around the courthouse square.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] This incorporation was short-lived, and Anderson once again went back to village status in 1852.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] However, with the completion of the Indianapolis Bellefontaine Railroad, as well as their station in 1852, Anderson burst to life.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The third incorporation of Anderson as a town occurred on June 9, 1853.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] On August 28, 1865, with a population of nearly 1,300 people, Anderson was incorporated as a city.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Between 1853 and the late 19th century, twenty industries of various sizes located there.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] On March 31, 1887, natural gas was discovered in Anderson.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] As the Indiana gas boom began, this discovery led new businesses that could use natural gas, such as glass-making, to move to the city.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Anderson grew to such proportions that a Cincinnati newspaper editor labeled the city "The Pittsburgh on White River".
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Other appellations were "Queen City of the Gas Belt" and (because of the vulcanizing and rubber tire manufacturing business) "Puncture Proof City".
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] In 1897 the Interurban Railroad was born in Anderson.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Charles Henry, a large stock holder, coined the term "Interurban" in 1893.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The Commercial Club (formed on November 18, 1905) was the forerunner of the present chamber of commerce.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The year 1912 spelled disaster for Anderson: the natural gas ran out.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The city had left its gas-powered lights on day and night, and there are stories of a pocket of natural gas being lit in the river and burning for a prolonged period for the spectacle of it.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The result of the loss of natural gas was that several factories moved out.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] This club persuaded the Remy brothers to stay in Anderson and others to locate there.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] For decades, Delco Remy and Guide Lamp (later Fisher Guide), which during World War II built the M3 submachine gun and the FP-45 Liberator pistol for the Allies, were the top two employers in the city.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] From 1913 through the 1950s, the Ward-Stilson Company was one of the country's largest producers of uniforms, regalia, furniture and props for the Freemasons, the Odd Fellows, and dozens of other U.S. fraternal organizations.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The Church of God of Anderson located its world headquarters in Anderson in 1905.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Anderson Bible School was opened in 1917, and this was separated from Gospel Trumpet (now known as Warner Press) in 1925.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] At the same time, it became known as Anderson Bible School and Seminary.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] In 1925, the name was changed to Anderson College and eventually to Anderson University in 1988.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Over the years, 17 different types of automobiles were manufactured in Anderson, with the Lambert family among the city's leaders in its development and the Buckeye Gasoline Buggy the Lambert product.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Many other inventions were perfected in Anderson, including the gas regulator (Miron G.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Reynolds), the stamp vending machine (Frank P.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Donald Forse), "Irish Mail" handcars (Hugh Hill), flower car for funeral homes (Francis M.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Polhemus)), Sisson choke (Glenn Sisson), and the vulcanizing process to retread tires (Charles E.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Anderson hosted a National Basketball Association (NBA) franchise for the 1949–50 season, being one of the smaller cities to have had a major league franchise in a Big Four American sport.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The Anderson Packers were a founding member of the NBA (under that name), but folded after one season.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Like most other industrial cities in Indiana and the Rust Belt as a whole, Anderson suffered tremendously from deindustrialization in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] For example, nearly 22,000 people were employed by General Motors in the 1970s in Anderson; by 2006 this number had declined to fewer than 2,600.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Anderson has since struggled with higher rates of poverty and unemployment.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The city of Anderson occupies all of Anderson Township except for the much smaller communities of Country Club Heights, Edgewood, River Forest, and Woodlawn Heights, as well as small parts of five other townships: Lafayette, Richland, Union, Adams, and Fall Creek.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Indiana State Road 32 (14th Street) crosses the city center, leading east-northeast 19 miles (31 km) to Muncie and west-southwest the same distance to Noblesville.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] State Road 9 (Scatterfield Road) crosses the east side of the city, leading north 11 miles (18 km) to Alexandria and southwest 10 miles (16 km) to Pendleton.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Interstate 69 crosses the southeast corner of the city, with access from Exit 226 (SR 9/SR 109).
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] I-69 leads southwest 40 miles (64 km) to Indianapolis and northeast 83 miles (134 km) to Fort Wayne.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Census Bureau, Anderson has a total area of 41.7 square miles (108.00 km2), of which 41.6 square miles (108 km2) are land and 0.1 square miles (0.3 km2), or 0.27%, are water.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The White River flows east to west through the northern part of the city.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] As of the 2020 census, Anderson had a population of 54,788.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] 21.6% of residents were under the age of 18 and 19.1% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] For every 100 females there were 92.8 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 89.3 males age 18 and over.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] 97.9% of residents lived in urban areas, while 2.1% lived in rural areas.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] There were 23,484 households in Anderson, of which 26.1% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Of all households, 32.3% were married-couple households, 22.8% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 35.5% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] About 36.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 15.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] There were 27,250 housing units, of which 13.8% were vacant.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The homeowner vacancy rate was 2.3% and the rental vacancy rate was 11.1%.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] As of the 2010 census, there were people, households, and families living in the city.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The population density was 1,356.8 inhabitants per square mile (523.9/km2).
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] There were housing units at an average density of 675.7 per square mile (260.9/km2).
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The racial makeup of the city was 78.8% White, 15.2% African American, 0.3% Native American, 0.5% Asian, 2.6% from other races, and 2.6% from two or more races.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 4.8% of the population.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Of the extant households 28.8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 35.8% were married couples living together, 17.1% had a female householder with no husband present, 5.5% had a male householder with no wife present, and 41.6% were non-families.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] 34.5% of all households were made up of individuals, and 13.8% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The average household size was 2.28 and the average family size was 2.91.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The median age in the city was 37.8 years.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] 22.4% of residents were under the age of 18; 11.5% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 24.8% were from 25 to 44; 24.9% were from 45 to 64; and 16.3% were 65 years of age or older.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The gender makeup of the city was 47.9% male and 52.1% female.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] As of the 2000 census, there were people, households, and families living in the city.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The population density was 1,491.6 inhabitants per square mile (575.9/km2).
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] There were housing units at an average density of 690.3 per square mile (266.5/km2).
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The racial makeup of the city was 81.99% White, 14.88% African American, 0.31% Native American, 0.49% Asian, 0.02% Pacific Islander, 0.86% from other races, and 1.45% from two or more races.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 2.07% of the population.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] There were 25,274 households, out of which 27.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 41.4% were married couples living together, 15.1% had a female householder with no husband present, and 39.0% were non-families.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] 33.1% of all households were made up of individuals, and 14.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The average household size was 2.28 and the average family size was 2.87.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] In the city, the age distribution of the population shows 23.2% under the age of 18, 11.2% from 18 to 24, 27.6% from 25 to 44, 21.3% from 45 to 64, and 16.6% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The city government consists of a mayor and a city council.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The city council consists of nine members.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Six are elected from individual districts.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] When General Motors closed its operations in Anderson, the city was dealt a major economic blow, as GM was the biggest employer in Anderson.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Nevertheless, in 2007, Anderson was ranked 98th in the *Forbes* List for 100 Best Places for Businesses among Smaller U.S.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] However, a more recent (2014) appraisal of Anderson from the *Indiana Business Review* was mixed, noting that "long-term trends are negative", citing "a long-term downward trend in area employment" and "acceleration in the number of food stamp recipients".
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] More recent unemployment has been reduced, but improvements still lag behind the rest of the state.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] For 2013, estimated household median income was $33,574 (vs.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Per capita money income was $18,216 (Indiana per capita of $24,635).
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] 25.8% of the city's population was estimated at living below poverty level, vs. a statewide estimation of 15.4%.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Madison County, of which Anderson is the seat, has nearly three times as many food stamps recipients per capita as does Indiana as a whole.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Until 1997, Anderson had three high schools: Highland, Madison Heights and Anderson.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] In 1997 Madison Heights was closed and Anderson High School moved into that facility.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Beginning in the fall of 2010, Highland High School closed and was converted into a junior high school, consolidating all students in grades 9-12 into Anderson High School.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Small portions of the city limits are in the South Madison Community School Corporation.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Anderson also has a charter school (non-traditional, tuition-free public school) called Anderson Preparatory Academy.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Currently, Anderson Preparatory Academy features grades K-12.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Anderson Preparatory Academy is a college preparatory, military-based academy.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] All cadets in grades 6-8 are members of the Civil Air Patrol.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] High school cadets are all members of the Air Force JROTC program.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Original plans called to only offer grades 6–9, then add on another upper grade each year before extending the lower years.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] Anderson University is within the city, as are a campus of the Ivy Tech Community College of Indiana and a campus of the Purdue Polytechnic Institute.
[src:charlie-knepper/anderson-indiana] The city has a lending library, the Anderson Public Library.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The initial objective of the batting team is to have a player reach first base safely; this occurs either when the batter hits the ball and reaches first base before an opponent retrieves the ball and touches the base, or when the pitcher persists in throwing the ball out of the batter's reach.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Players on the batting team who reach first base without being called "out" can attempt to advance to subsequent bases as a runner, either immediately or during teammates' turns batting.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The fielding team tries to prevent runs by using the ball to get batters or runners "out", which forces them out of the field of play.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The pitcher can get the batter out by throwing three pitches which result in strikes, while fielders can get the batter out by catching a batted ball before it touches the ground, and can get a runner out by tagging them with the ball while the runner is not touching a base.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The opposing teams switch back and forth between batting and fielding; the batting team's turn to bat is over once the fielding team records three outs.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] One turn batting for each team constitutes an inning.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A game is usually composed of nine innings, and the team with the greater number of runs at the end of the game wins.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Most games end after the ninth inning, but if scores are tied at that point, extra innings are usually played.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Baseball has no game clock, though some competitions feature pace-of-play regulations such as a pitch clock to shorten game time.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Baseball evolved from older bat-and-ball games already being played in England by the mid-18th century.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] This game was brought by immigrants to North America, where the modern version developed.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In addition to North America, baseball spread throughout the rest of the Americas and the Asia–Pacific in the 19th and 20th centuries, and is now considered the most popular sport in parts of Central and South America, the Caribbean, and East Asia, particularly in Japan, South Korea, and Taiwan.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In Major League Baseball (MLB), the highest level of professional baseball in the United States and Canada, teams are divided into the National League (NL) and American League (AL), each with three divisions: East, West, and Central.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The MLB champion is determined by playoffs that culminate in the World Series.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The top level of play is similarly split in Japan between the Central and Pacific Leagues and in Cuba between the West League and East League.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The World Baseball Classic, organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation, is the major international competition of the sport and attracts the top national teams from around the world.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Baseball was played at the Olympic Games from 1992 to 2008, and was reinstated on a one-off basis in 2020.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A baseball game is played between two teams, each composed of nine players, that take turns playing offense (batting and baserunning) and defense (pitching and fielding).
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A pair of turns, one at bat and one in the field, by each team constitutes an inning.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A game consists of nine innings (seven innings at the high school level and in doubleheaders in college and Minor League Baseball; and six innings at the Little League level).
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] One team—customarily the visiting team—bats in the top, or first half, of every inning.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The other team—customarily the home team—bats in the bottom, or second half, of every inning.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The goal of the game is to score more points (runs) than the other team.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The players on the team at bat attempt to score runs by touching all four bases, in order, set at the corners of the square-shaped baseball diamond.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A player bats at home plate and must attempt to safely reach a base before proceeding, counterclockwise, from first base, to second base, third base, and back home to score a run.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The team in the field attempts to prevent runs from scoring by recording outs, which remove opposing players from offensive action until their next turn at bat comes up again.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] When three outs are recorded, the teams switch roles for the next half-inning.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] If the score of the game is tied after nine innings, extra innings are played to resolve the contest.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Many amateur games, particularly unorganized ones, involve different numbers of players and innings.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The game is played on a field whose primary boundaries, the foul lines, extend forward from home plate at 45-degree angles.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The 90-degree area within the foul lines is referred to as fair territory; the 270-degree area outside them is foul territory.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The part of the field enclosed by the bases and several yards beyond them is the infield; the area farther beyond the infield is the outfield.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In the middle of the infield is a raised pitcher's mound, with a rectangular rubber plate (the rubber) at its center.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The outer boundary of the outfield is typically demarcated by a raised fence, which may be of any material and height.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The fair territory between home plate and the outfield boundary is baseball's field of play, though significant events can take place in foul territory, as well.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Protective helmets are also standard equipment for all batters.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] At the beginning of each half-inning, the nine players of the fielding team arrange themselves around the field.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] One of them, the pitcher, stands on the pitcher's mound.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The pitcher begins the pitching delivery with one foot on the rubber, pushing off it to gain velocity when throwing toward home plate.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Another fielding team player, the catcher, squats on the far side of home plate, facing the pitcher.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The rest of the fielding team faces home plate, typically arranged as four infielders—who set up along or within a few yards outside the imaginary lines (basepaths) between first, second, and third base—and three outfielders.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In the standard arrangement, there is a first baseman positioned several steps to the left of first base, a second baseman to the right of second base, a shortstop to the left of second base, and a third baseman to the right of third base.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The basic outfield positions are left fielder, center fielder, and right fielder.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] With the exception of the catcher, all fielders are required to be in fair territory when the pitch is delivered.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A neutral umpire sets up behind the catcher.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Other umpires will be distributed around the field as well.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Play starts with a member of the batting team, the batter, standing in either of the two batter's boxes next to home plate, holding a bat.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The batter waits for the pitcher to throw a pitch (the ball) toward home plate, and attempts to hit the ball with the bat.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The catcher catches pitches that the batter does not hit—as a result of either electing not to swing or failing to connect—and returns them to the pitcher.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A batter who hits the ball into the field of play must drop the bat and begin running toward first base, at which point the player is referred to as a *runner* (or, until the play is over, a *batter-runner*).
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A batter-runner who reaches first base without being put out is said to be *safe* and is on base.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A batter-runner may choose to remain at first base or attempt to advance to second base or even beyond—however far the player believes can be reached safely.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base despite proper play by the fielders has recorded a hit.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A player who reaches first base safely on a hit is credited with a single.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] If a player makes it to second base safely as a direct result of a hit, it is a double; third base, a triple.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air within the foul lines over the entire outfield (and outfield fence, if there is one), or if the batter-runner otherwise safely circles all the bases, it is a home run: the batter and any runners on base may all freely circle the bases, each scoring a run.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] This is the most desirable result for the batter.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The ultimate and most desirable result possible for a batter would be to hit a home run while all three bases are occupied or "loaded", thus scoring four runs on a single hit.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base due to a fielding mistake is not credited with a hit—instead, the responsible fielder is charged with an error.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Any runners already on base may attempt to advance on batted balls that land, or contact the ground, in fair territory, before or after the ball lands.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A runner on first base *must* attempt to advance if a ball lands in play, as only one runner may occupy a base at any given time; the same applies for other runners if they are on a base that a teammate is forced to advance to.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] If a ball hit into play rolls foul before passing through the infield, it becomes dead and any runners must return to the base they occupied when the play began.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air and caught before it lands, the batter has flied out and any runners on base may attempt to advance only if they tag up (contact the base they occupied when the play began, as or after the ball is caught).
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Runners may also attempt to advance to the next base while the pitcher is in the process of delivering the ball to home plate; a successful effort is a stolen base.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A pitch that is not hit into the field of play is called either a strike or a ball.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A batter against whom three strikes are recorded strikes out.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A batter against whom four balls are recorded is awarded a base on balls or walk, a free advance to first base.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] While the team at bat is trying to score runs, the team in the field is attempting to record outs.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In addition to the strikeout and flyout, common ways a member of the batting team may be put out include the ground out, force out, and tag out.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] These occur either when a runner is forced to advance to a base, and a fielder with possession of the ball reaches that base before the runner does, or the runner is touched by the ball, held in a fielder's hand, while not on a base.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] (The batter-runner is always forced to advance to first base, and any other runners must advance to the next base if a teammate is forced to advance to their base.) It is possible to record two outs in the course of the same play.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Three outs in one play, a triple play, is possible, though rare.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Players put out or retired must leave the field, returning to their team's dugout or bench.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A runner may be stranded on base when a third out is recorded against another player on the team.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Stranded runners do not benefit the team in its next turn at bat as every half-inning begins with the bases empty.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] An individual player's turn batting or plate appearance is complete when the player reaches base, hits a home run, makes an out, or hits a ball that results in the team's third out, even if it is recorded against a teammate.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] On rare occasions, a batter may be at the plate when, without the batter's hitting the ball, a third out is recorded against a teammate—for instance, a runner getting caught stealing (tagged out attempting to steal a base).
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A batter with this sort of incomplete plate appearance starts off the team's next turn batting; any balls or strikes recorded against the batter the previous inning are erased.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A runner may circle the bases only once per plate appearance and thus can score at most a single run per batting turn.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Once a player has completed a plate appearance, that player may not bat again until the eight other members of the player's team have all taken their turn at bat in the batting order.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The batting order is set before the game begins, and may not be altered except for substitutions.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Once a player has been removed for a substitute, that player may not reenter the game.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Children's games often have more lenient rules, such as Little League rules, which allow players to be substituted back into the same game.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] If the designated hitter (DH) rule is in effect, each team has a tenth player whose sole responsibility is to bat (and run).
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The DH takes the place of another player—almost invariably the pitcher—in the batting order, but does not field.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Thus, even with the DH, each team still has a batting order of nine players and a fielding arrangement of nine players.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The number of players on a baseball roster, or *squad*, varies by league and by the level of organized play.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A Major League Baseball (MLB) team has a roster of 26 players with specific roles.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Most baseball leagues worldwide have the DH rule, including MLB, Japan's Pacific League, and Caribbean professional leagues, along with major American amateur organizations.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The Central League in Japan does not have the rule and high-level minor league clubs connected to National League teams are not required to field a DH.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In leagues that apply the designated hitter rule, a typical team has nine offensive regulars (including the DH), five starting pitchers, seven or eight relievers, a backup catcher, and two or three other reserve players.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The manager, or head coach, oversees the team's major strategic decisions, such as establishing the starting rotation, setting the lineup, or batting order, before each game, and making substitutions during games—in particular, bringing in relief pitchers.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Managers are typically assisted by two or more coaches; they may have specialized responsibilities, such as working with players on hitting, fielding, pitching, or strength and conditioning.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] At most levels of organized play, two coaches are stationed on the field when the team is at bat: the first base coach and third base coach, who occupy designated coaches' boxes, just outside the foul lines.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] These coaches assist in the direction of baserunners, when the ball is in play, and relay tactical signals from the manager to batters and runners, during pauses in play.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In contrast to many other team sports, baseball managers and coaches generally wear their team's uniforms; coaches must be in uniform to be allowed on the field to confer with players during a game.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Any baseball game involves one or more umpires, who make rulings on the outcome of each play.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] At a minimum, one umpire will stand behind the catcher, to have a good view of the strike zone, and call balls and strikes.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Additional umpires may be stationed near the other bases, thus making it easier to judge plays such as attempted force outs and tag outs.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In MLB, four umpires are used for each game, one near each base.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In the playoffs, six umpires are used: one at each base and two in the outfield along the foul lines.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Many of the pre-game and in-game strategic decisions in baseball revolve around a fundamental fact: in general, right-handed batters tend to be more successful against left-handed pitchers and, to an even greater degree, left-handed batters tend to be more successful against right-handed pitchers.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A manager with several left-handed batters in the regular lineup, who knows the team will be facing a left-handed starting pitcher, may respond by starting one or more of the right-handed backups on the team's roster.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] During the late innings of a game, as relief pitchers and pinch hitters are brought in, the opposing managers will often go back and forth trying to create favorable matchups with their substitutions.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The manager of the fielding team trying to arrange same-handed pitcher-batter matchups and the manager of the batting team trying to arrange opposite-handed matchups.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] With a team that has the lead in the late innings, a manager may remove a starting position player—especially one whose turn at bat is not likely to come up again—for a more skillful fielder (known as a defensive substitution).
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The tactical decision that precedes almost every play in a baseball game involves pitch selection.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] By gripping and then releasing the baseball in a certain manner, and by throwing it at a certain speed, pitchers can cause the baseball to break to either side, or downward, as it approaches the batter, thus creating differing pitches that can be selected.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Among the resulting wide variety of pitches that may be thrown, the four basic types are the fastball, the changeup (or off-speed pitch), and two breaking balls—the curveball and the slider.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Pitchers have different repertoires of pitches they are skillful at throwing.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Conventionally, before each pitch, the catcher signals the pitcher what type of pitch to throw, as well as its general vertical or horizontal location.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] If there is disagreement on the selection, the pitcher may shake off the sign and the catcher will call for a different pitch.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] With a runner on base and taking a lead, the pitcher may attempt a pickoff, a quick throw to a fielder covering the base to keep the runner's lead in check or, optimally, effect a tag out.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Pickoff attempts, however, are subject to rules that severely restrict the pitcher's movements before and during the pickoff attempt.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Violation of any one of these rules could result in the umpire calling a balk against the pitcher, which permits any runners on base to advance one base with impunity.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] If an attempted stolen base is anticipated, the catcher may call for a pitchout, a ball thrown deliberately off the plate, allowing the catcher to catch it while standing and throw quickly to a base.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Facing a batter with a strong tendency to hit to one side of the field, the fielding team may employ a shift, with most or all of the fielders moving to the left or right of their usual positions.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] With a runner on third base, the infielders may play in, moving closer to home plate to improve the odds of throwing out the runner on a ground ball, though a sharply hit grounder is more likely to carry through a drawn-in infield.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Several basic offensive tactics come into play with a runner on first base, including the fundamental choice of whether to attempt a steal of second base.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The hit and run is sometimes employed, with a skillful contact hitter, the runner takes off with the pitch, drawing the shortstop or second baseman over to second base, creating a gap in the infield for the batter to poke the ball through.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The sacrifice bunt, calls for the batter to focus on making soft contact with the ball, so that it rolls a short distance into the infield, allowing the runner to advance into scoring position as the batter is thrown out at first.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A batter, particularly one who is a fast runner, may also attempt to bunt for a hit.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A sacrifice bunt employed with a runner on third base, aimed at bringing that runner home, is known as a squeeze play.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] With a runner on third and fewer than two outs, a batter may instead concentrate on hitting a fly ball that, even if it is caught, will be deep enough to allow the runner to tag up and score—a successful batter, in this case, gets credit for a sacrifice fly.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In order to increase the chance of advancing a batter to first base via a walk, the manager will sometimes signal a batter who is ahead in the count (i.e., has more balls than strikes) to take, or not swing at, the next pitch.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The batter's potential reward of reaching base (via a walk) exceeds the disadvantage if the next pitch is a strike.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Consensus once held that today's baseball is a North American development from the older game rounders, popular among children in Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] American baseball historian David Block suggests that the game originated in England; recently uncovered historical evidence supports this position.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] According to Block and official MLB historian John Thorn, this earlier version of baseball may have involved hitting the ball with a hand, making it akin to today's punchball.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Block argues that rounders and early baseball were actually regional variants of each other, and that the game's most direct antecedents are the English games of stoolball and "tut-ball".
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The earliest known reference to baseball is in a 1744 British publication, *A Little Pretty Pocket-Book*, by John Newbery.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Block discovered that the first recorded game of "Base Ball" took place in 1749 in Surrey, and featured the Prince of Wales as a player.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] This early form of the game was apparently brought to Canada by English immigrants.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] By the early 1830s, there were reports of a variety of uncodified bat-and-ball games recognizable as early forms of baseball being played around North America.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The first recorded baseball game in North America was played in Beachville, Ontario, Canada, on June 4, 1838.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In 1845, Alexander Cartwright, a member of New York City's Knickerbocker Club, led the codification of the so-called Knickerbocker Rules, which in turn were based on rules developed in 1837 by William R.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] While there are reports that the New York Knickerbockers played games in 1845, the contest long recognized as the first recorded baseball game in U.S. history took place on June 19, 1846, in Hoboken, New Jersey: the "New York Nine" defeated the Knickerbockers, 23–1, in four innings.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] With the Knickerbocker code as the basis, the rules of modern baseball continued to evolve over the next half-century.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The game then went on to spread throughout the Pacific Rim and the Americas, with Americans backing the sport as a way to spread American values.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In the mid-1850s, a baseball craze hit the New York metropolitan area, and by 1856, local journals were referring to baseball as the "national pastime" or "national game".
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A year later, the sport's first governing body, the National Association of Base Ball Players, was formed.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In 1867, it barred participation by African Americans.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The more formally structured National League was founded in 1876.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Professional Negro leagues formed, but quickly folded.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In 1887, softball, under the name of indoor baseball or indoor-outdoor, was invented as a winter version of the parent game.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The American League evolved from the minor Western League, which was reorganized under Ban Johnson in 1893.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] It was not until 1901 that the American League was formally established as a major league.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] By 1893, crucial structural changes (like moving the pitching distance to 60 feet, 6 inches) firmly cemented the modern rulebook.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The National Agreement of 1903 formalized relations both between the two major leagues and between them and the National Association of Professional Base Ball Leagues, representing most of the country's minor professional leagues.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The World Series, pitting the two major league champions against each other, was inaugurated that fall.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The Black Sox Scandal of the 1919 World Series led to the formation of the office of the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The first commissioner, Kenesaw Mountain Landis, was elected in 1920.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] That year also saw the founding of the Negro National League; the first significant Negro league, it would operate until 1931.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] For part of the 1920s, it was joined by the Eastern Colored League.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Compared with the present, professional baseball in the early 20th century was lower-scoring, and pitchers were more dominant.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] This so-called "dead-ball era" ended in the early 1920s with several changes in rule and circumstance that were advantageous to hitters.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Strict new regulations that governed the ball's size, shape and composition, along with a new rule officially banning the spitball and other pitches that depended on the ball being treated or roughed-up with foreign substances, resulted in a ball that traveled farther when hit.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The rise of the legendary player Babe Ruth, the first great power hitter of the new era, helped permanently alter the nature of the game.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Louis Cardinals general manager Branch Rickey invested in several minor league clubs and developed the first modern farm system.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A new Negro National League was organized in 1933; four years later, it was joined by the Negro American League.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The first elections to the National Baseball Hall of Fame took place in 1936.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In 1939, Little League Baseball was founded in Pennsylvania.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Many minor league teams disbanded when World War II led to a player shortage.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Wrigley led the formation of the All-American Girls Professional Baseball League to help keep the game in the public eye.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The first crack in the unwritten agreement barring blacks from white-controlled professional ball occurred in 1945: Jackie Robinson was signed by the National League's Brooklyn Dodgers and began playing for their minor league team in Montreal.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In 1947, Robinson broke the major leagues' color barrier when he debuted with the Dodgers.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Latin-American players, largely overlooked before, also started entering the majors in greater numbers.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In 1951, two Chicago White Sox, Venezuelan-born Chico Carrasquel and black Cuban-born Minnie Miñoso, became the first Hispanic All-Stars.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Integration proceeded slowly: by 1953, only six of the 16 major league teams had a black player on the roster.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In 1975, the union's power—and players' salaries—began to increase greatly when the reserve clause was effectively struck down, leading to the free agency system.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Significant work stoppages occurred in 1981 and 1994, the latter forcing the cancellation of the World Series for the first time in 90 years.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Attendance had been growing steadily since the mid-1970s and in 1994, before the stoppage, the majors were setting their all-time record for per-game attendance.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] After play resumed in 1995, non-division-winning wild card teams became a permanent fixture of the post-season.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Regular-season interleague play was introduced in 1997 and the second-highest attendance mark for a full season was set.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In 2000, the National and American Leagues were dissolved as legal entities.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] While their identities were maintained for scheduling purposes (and the designated hitter distinction), the regulations and other functions—such as player discipline and umpire supervision—they had administered separately were consolidated under the rubric of MLB.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In 2001, Barry Bonds established the current record of 73 home runs in a single season.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In 2007, Bonds became MLB's all-time home run leader, surpassing Hank Aaron, as total major league and minor league attendance both reached all-time highs.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Despite having been called "America's national pastime", baseball is well-established in several other countries.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] As early as 1877, a professional league, the International Association, featured teams from both Canada and the United States.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] While baseball is widely played in Canada and many minor league teams have been based in the country, the American major leagues did not include a Canadian club until 1969, when the Montreal Expos joined the National League as an expansion team.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In 1977, the expansion Toronto Blue Jays joined the American League.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In 1847, American soldiers played what may have been the first baseball game in Mexico at Parque Los Berros in Xalapa, Veracruz.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The first formal baseball league outside of the United States and Canada was founded in 1878 in Cuba, which maintains a rich baseball tradition.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The English football club, Aston Villa, were the first British baseball champions winning the 1890 National League of Baseball of Great Britain.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The 2025 National Champions were the London Mets.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The Dominican Republic held its first islandwide championship tournament in 1912.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Professional baseball tournaments and leagues began to form in other countries between the world wars, including the Netherlands (formed in 1922), Australia (1934), Japan (1936), Mexico (1937), and Puerto Rico (1938).
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The Japanese major leagues have long been considered the highest quality professional circuits outside of the United States.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] After World War II, professional leagues were founded in many Latin American countries, most prominently Venezuela (1946) and the Dominican Republic (1955).
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Since the early 1970s, the annual Caribbean Series has matched the championship clubs from the four leading Latin American winter leagues: the Dominican Professional Baseball League, Mexican Pacific League, Puerto Rican Professional Baseball League, and Venezuelan Professional Baseball League.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In Asia, South Korea (1982), Taiwan (1990) and China (2003) all have professional leagues.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Other European countries have seen professional leagues; the most successful, other than the Dutch league, is the Italian league, founded in 1948.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In 2004, Australia won a surprise silver medal at the Olympic Games.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The Confédération Européene de Baseball (European Baseball Confederation), founded in 1953, organizes a number of competitions between clubs from different countries.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Women's baseball is played on an organized amateur basis in numerous countries.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] After being admitted to the Olympics as a medal sport beginning with the 1992 Games, baseball was dropped from the 2012 Summer Olympic Games at the 2005 International Olympic Committee meeting.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] While the sport's lack of a following in much of the world was a factor, more important was MLB's reluctance to allow its players to participate during the major league season.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] MLB initiated the World Baseball Classic, scheduled to precede its season, partly as a replacement, high-profile international tournament.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The inaugural Classic, held in March 2006, was the first tournament involving national teams to feature a significant number of MLB participants.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The Baseball World Cup was discontinued after its 2011 edition in favor of an expanded World Baseball Classic.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Baseball has certain attributes that set it apart from the other popular team sports in the countries where it has a following.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] All of these sports use a clock, play is less individual, and the variation between playing fields is not as substantial or important.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The comparison between cricket and baseball demonstrates that many of baseball's distinctive elements are shared in various ways with similar sports.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In clock-limited sports, games often end with a team that holds the lead killing the clock rather than competing aggressively against the opposing team.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In contrast, baseball has no clock, thus a team cannot win without getting the last batter out and rallies are not constrained by time.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] At almost any turn in any baseball game, the most advantageous strategy is some form of aggressive strategy.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] While nine innings has been the standard since the beginning of professional baseball, the duration of the average major league game has increased steadily through the years.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] At the turn of the 20th century, games typically took an hour and a half to play.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In the 1920s, they averaged just less than two hours, which eventually ballooned to 2:38 in 1960.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] By 1997, the average American League game lasted 2:57 (National League games were about 10 minutes shorter—pitchers at the plate making for quicker outs than designated hitters).
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In 2004, Major League Baseball declared that its goal was an average game of 2:45.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] By 2014, though, the average MLB game took over three hours to complete.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The lengthening of games is attributed to longer breaks between half-innings for television commercials, increased offense, more pitching changes, and a slower pace of play, with pitchers taking more time between each delivery, and batters stepping out of the box more frequently.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Other leagues have experienced similar issues.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In 2008, Nippon Professional Baseball took steps aimed at shortening games by 12 minutes from the preceding decade's average of 3:18.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In 2016, the average nine-inning playoff game in Major League baseball was 3 hours and 35 minutes.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] This was up 10 minutes from 2015 and 21 minutes from 2014.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In response to the lengthening of the game, MLB decided from the 2023 season onward to institute a pitch clock rule to penalize batters and pitchers who take too much time between pitches; this had the effect of shortening 2023 regular season games by 24 minutes on average.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Although baseball is a team sport, individual players are often placed under scrutiny and pressure.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] While rewarding, it has sometimes been described as "ruthless" due to the pressure on the individual player.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] In 1915, a baseball instructional manual pointed out that every single pitch, of which there are often more than two hundred in a game, involves an individual, one-on-one contest: "the pitcher and the batter in a battle of wits".
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Pitcher, batter, and fielder all act essentially independent of each other.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] While coaching staffs can signal pitcher or batter to pursue certain tactics, the execution of the play itself is a series of solitary acts.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] If the batter hits a line drive, the outfielder is solely responsible for deciding to try to catch it or play it on the bounce and for succeeding or failing.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The statistical precision of baseball is both facilitated by this isolation and reinforces it.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] There is no statistical equivalent in cricket for the fielding error and thus less emphasis on personal responsibility in this area of play.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Unlike those of most sports, baseball playing fields can vary significantly in size and shape.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Major league teams often skirt even this rule.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] For example, at Daikin Park, which became the home of the Houston Astros in 2000, the Crawford Boxes in left field are only 315 feet (96 m) from home plate.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] There are no rules at all that address the height of fences or other structures at the edge of the outfield.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The most famously idiosyncratic outfield boundary is the left-field wall at Boston's Fenway Park, in use since 1912: the Green Monster is 310 feet (94 m) from home plate down the line and 37 feet (11 m) tall.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Similarly, there are no regulations at all concerning the dimensions of foul territory.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Thus a foul fly ball may be entirely out of play in a park with little space between the foul lines and the stands, but a foulout in a park with more expansive foul ground.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A fence in foul territory that is close to the outfield line will tend to direct balls that strike it back toward the fielders, while one that is farther away may actually prompt more collisions, as outfielders run full speed to field balls deep in the corner.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] These variations can make the difference between a double and a triple or inside-the-park home run.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The surface of the field is also unregulated.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] While the adjacent image shows a traditional field surfacing arrangement (and the one used by virtually all MLB teams with naturally surfaced fields), teams are free to decide what areas will be grassed or bare.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Some fields—including several in MLB—use artificial turf.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Surface variations can have a significant effect on how ground balls behave and are fielded as well as on baserunning.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Similarly, the presence of a roof (seven major league teams play in stadiums with permanent or retractable roofs) can greatly affect how fly balls are played.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] While football and soccer players deal with similar variations of field surface and stadium covering, the size and shape of their fields are much more standardized.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The area out-of-bounds on a football or soccer field does not affect play the way foul territory in baseball does, so variations in that regard are largely insignificant.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] These physical variations create a distinctive set of playing conditions at each ballpark.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Other local factors, such as altitude and climate, can also significantly affect play.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A given stadium may acquire a reputation as a pitcher's park or a hitter's park, if one or the other discipline notably benefits from its unique mix of elements.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The most exceptional park in this regard is Coors Field, home of the Colorado Rockies.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Its high altitude—5,282 feet (1,610 m) above sea level—is partly responsible for giving it the strongest hitter's park effect in the major leagues due to the low air pressure.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] Wrigley Field, home of the Chicago Cubs, is known for its fickle disposition: a pitcher's park when the strong winds off Lake Michigan are blowing in, it becomes more of a hitter's park when they are blowing out.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] The absence of a standardized field affects not only how particular games play out, but the nature of team rosters and players' statistical records.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] For example, hitting a fly ball 330 feet (100 m) into right field might result in an easy catch on the warning track at one park, and a home run at another.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] A team that plays in a park with a relatively short right field, such as the New York Yankees, will tend to stock its roster with left-handed pull hitters, who can best exploit it.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p01] On the individual level, a player who spends most of his career with a team that plays in a hitter's park will gain an advantage in batting statistics over time—even more so if his talents are especially suited to the park.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Organized baseball lends itself to statistics to a greater degree than many other sports.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Each play is discrete and has a relatively small number of possible outcomes.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] The Official Baseball Rules administered by MLB require the official scorer to categorize each baseball play unambiguously.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] The rules provide detailed criteria to promote consistency.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] The score report is the official basis for both the box score of the game and the relevant statistical records.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] General managers, managers, and baseball scouts use statistics to evaluate players and make strategic decisions.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Certain traditional statistics are familiar to most baseball fans.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Among the many other statistics that are kept are those collectively known as *situational statistics*.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] For example, statistics can indicate which specific pitchers a certain batter performs best against.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] If a given situation statistically favors a certain batter, the manager of the fielding team may be more likely to change pitchers or have the pitcher intentionally walk the batter in order to face one who is less likely to succeed.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Sabermetrics is the field of baseball statistical study and the development of new statistics and analytical tools.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Such new statistics are also called sabermetrics.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] The term was coined around 1980 by one of the field's leading proponents, Bill James, and derives from the Society for American Baseball Research (SABR).
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Writing in 1919, philosopher Morris Raphael Cohen described baseball as the national religion of the US.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] In the words of sports columnist Jayson Stark, baseball has long been "a unique paragon of American culture"—a status he sees as devastated by the steroid abuse scandal.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] American influence in the Western Hemisphere has meant that baseball grew significantly in the region.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] A century later, the situation was very different.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] With the rise in popularity of other team sports with much higher average ticket prices—football, basketball, and hockey—professional baseball had become among the most popular blue-collar-oriented American spectator sports.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Overall, baseball has a large following in the United States; a 2006 poll found that nearly half of Americans are fans.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] This led to baseball being granted the title of "America's favorite pastime" by many American baseball fans.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] As historians and scholars now speculate, baseball is a metaphor of the American way of life In the late 1900s and early 2000s, baseball's position compared to football in the United States moved in contradictory directions.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] In 2008, MLB set a revenue record of $6.5 billion, matching the NFL's revenue for the first time in decades.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] A new MLB revenue record of more than $10 billion was set in 2017.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] On the other hand, the percentage of American sports fans polled who named baseball as their favorite sport was 9%, compared to pro football at 37%.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] In 1985, the respective figures were pro football 24%, baseball 23%.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Because there are so many more major league games played, there is no comparison in overall attendance.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] In 2008, total attendance at major league games was the second-highest in history: 78.6 million, 0.7% off the record set the previous year.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] The following year, amid the U.S. recession, attendance fell by 6.6% to 73.4 million.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Eight years later, it dropped under 73 million.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Attendance at games held under the Minor League Baseball umbrella set a record in 2008, with 43.3 million.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] While MLB games have not drawn the same national TV viewership as football games, MLB games are dominant in teams' local markets and regularly lead all programs in primetime in their markets during the summer.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] After multiple years of declines since 2017, baseball attendance has grown slightly in recent years.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] In 2024, attendance was 71.3 million, the highest since 2017.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Baseball is very popular in Venezuela; in 2011, 95% of people surveyed claimed it to be the national sport.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] In Nicaragua and Panama, baseball is also considered the national sport.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] While soccer is still more popular, baseball is a fast-growing sport in Mexico.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] In 2024, top Mexican League baseball teams outdraw some Liga MX teams in attendance.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Baseball also is somewhat popular in Colombia, though secondary to soccer, especially in coastal areas such as Barranquilla and Cartagena which are near the Caribbean.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] In recent years, baseball has grown in popularity in Colombia, especially in the capital of Bogotá, due an increase of Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] In Brazil, baseball fan popularity has grown in the last few years, thanks to MLB broadcasts in Brazilian ESPN and the historic silver medal in 2023 Pan-American games.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] However, it still lags behind basketball and American football in the list of most played sports in Brazil.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Baseball has also grown in popularity in Argentina and Peru in recent years due to Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Costa Rica has also seen a growth in the popularity of baseball.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Since 1987, baseballs have exclusively been made in the Costa Rican town of Turrialba.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] In recent years, Major leaguer Mauricio Dubón has made efforts to increase support for the sport in the country.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] The sport's overall popularity in Latin America has assisted in integrating Latin American migrants to the United States.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Since the early 1980s, the Dominican Republic, in particular the city of San Pedro de Macorís, has been the major leagues' primary source of foreign talent.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] In 2017, 83 of the 868 players on MLB Opening Day rosters (and disabled lists) were from the country.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Among other Caribbean countries and territories, a combined 97 MLB players were born in Venezuela, Cuba, and Puerto Rico.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Hall-of-Famer Roberto Clemente remains one of the greatest national heroes in Puerto Rico's history.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] While baseball has long been the island's primary athletic pastime, its once well-attended professional winter league has declined in popularity since 1990, when young Puerto Rican players began to be included in the major leagues' annual first-year player draft.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] In Cuba, where baseball is by every reckoning the national sport, the national team overshadows the city and provincial teams that play in the top-level domestic leagues.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Baseball is also one of the most popular sports of Aruba and Curaçao, and a growing sport in The Bahamas and the US Virgin Islands.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] In East Asia, baseball is among the most popular sports in Japan, Taiwan and South Korea.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] In Japan, where baseball is inarguably the leading spectator team sport, combined revenue for the twelve teams in Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the body that oversees both the Central and Pacific Leagues, was estimated at $1 billion in 2007.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Total NPB attendance for the year was approximately 20 million.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] While in the preceding two decades, MLB attendance grew by 50 percent and revenue nearly tripled, the comparable NPB figures were stagnant.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] There are concerns that MLB's growing interest in acquiring star Japanese players will hurt the game in their home country.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Revenue figures are not released for the country's amateur system.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Similarly, according to one official pronouncement, the sport's governing authority "has never taken into account attendance ... because its greatest interest has always been the development of athletes".
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] In Taiwan, baseball is one of the most widely spectated sports, in TV and person.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown significantly in China in recent years, with MLB estimating in 2019 that there are 21 million active fans in the country.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Baseball was considered a national pastime in the Philippines in the 1960s and 70s, but the sport has since declined in popularity.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Since 2005, there have been efforts to revitalize the sport in the country.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Baseball saw a surge in popularity in Thailand following the countries' silver medal in baseball in the 2025 SEA Games, which were hosted in Thailand.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Baseball is generally a niche sport in Europe.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] However, baseball is somewhat popular in the Netherlands, where it is known as *honkbal*, thanks to influence from the United States after World War II and the Kingdoms control over Aruba and Curaçao where it is the most popular sport.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Baseball is also somewhat popular in portions of Italy, especially in the town of Nettuno, due to influence from American soldiers after World War II.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown in recent years in the Czech Republic, due in part to the Czech teams' success in the 2023 World Baseball Classic.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Baseball is one of the most popular sports in Palau and Guam.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] In Australia, baseball is a niche sport but the country does have a professional league.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Because the league is played in winter for the western hemisphere, it attracts American and Korean professional players looking to play winter league baseball.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] In 2026, there were more than 30 Australians playing college baseball in the United States compared to six in 2020.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] The Dodgers operate a large baseball academy in Mpigi, Uganda, and there are also baseball programs in Luwero, Uganda.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] There is also a Africa Baseball Academy in Nairobi, Nigeria.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Baseball was popular in South Africa prior to World War 2 but popularity has since waned.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] There are still teams and attempts to raise the popularity of baseball in the country, including the introduction of Baseball5.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] There is a growing baseball program in South Sudan, which has resulted in professional contracts.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] The Japan-Africa Baseball & Softball Foundation has created Koshien high school baseball tournaments in Tanzania, Ghana and Kenya, which Tanzania being the most successful.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] There are further plans for similar tournaments in Nigeria, South Sudan, Benin, Cameroon and Zambia.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] As of 2024, Little League Baseball oversees leagues with 2 million participants in more than 80 countries.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] The number of players has fallen since the 1990s, when 3 million children took part in Little League Baseball annually.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Babe Ruth League teams have over 1 million participants.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] According to the president of the International Baseball Federation in 2009, between 300,000 and 500,000 women and girls play baseball around the world, including Little League and the introductory game of Tee Ball.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] A varsity baseball team is an established part of physical education departments at most high schools and colleges in the United States.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] In 2015, nearly half a million high schoolers and over 34,000 collegians played on their schools' baseball teams.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] By early in the 20th century, intercollegiate baseball was Japan's leading sport.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Today, high school baseball in particular is immensely popular there.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] The final rounds of the two annual tournaments—the National High School Baseball Invitational Tournament in the spring, and the even more important National High School Baseball Championship in the summer—are broadcast around the country.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] The tournaments are known, respectively, as Spring Koshien and Summer Koshien after the 55,000-capacity stadium where they are played.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] In Cuba, baseball is a mandatory part of the state system of physical education, which begins at age six.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Talented children as young as seven are sent to special district schools for more intensive training—the first step on a ladder whose acme is the national baseball team.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Baseball has had a broad impact on popular culture, both in the United States and elsewhere.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Dozens of English-language idioms have been derived from baseball; in particular, the game is the source of a number of widely used sexual euphemisms.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] The first networked radio broadcasts in North America were of the 1922 World Series: famed sportswriter Grantland Rice announced play-by-play from New York City's Polo Grounds on WJZ–Newark, New Jersey, which was connected by wire to WGY–Schenectady, New York, and WBZ–Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] The baseball cap has become a ubiquitous fashion item not only in the United States and Japan, but also in countries where the sport itself is not particularly popular, such as the United Kingdom.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Baseball has inspired many works of art and entertainment.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] There have been many baseball movies, including the Academy Award–winning *The Pride of the Yankees* (1942) and the Oscar nominees *The Natural* (1984) and *Field of Dreams* (1989).
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] The American Film Institute's selection of the ten best sports movies includes *The Pride of the Yankees* at number 3 and *Bull Durham* (1988) at number 5.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Baseball has provided thematic material for hits on both stage—the Adler–Ross musical *Damn Yankees*—and record—George J.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Gaskin's "Slide, Kelly, Slide", Simon and Garfunkel's "Mrs.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Robinson", and John Fogerty's "Centerfield".
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] The baseball-inspired comedic sketch "Who's on First?", popularized by Abbott and Costello in 1938, quickly became famous; six decades later, *Time* named it the best comedy routine of the 20th century.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Literary works connected to the game include the short fiction of Ring Lardner and novels such as Bernard Malamud's *The Natural* (the source for the movie), Robert Coover's *The Universal Baseball Association, Inc., J.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Henry Waugh, Prop.*, John Grisham's Calico Joe and W.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Kinsella's *Shoeless Joe* (the source for *Field of Dreams*).
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Baseball's literary canon also includes the beat reportage of Damon Runyon; the columns of Grantland Rice, Red Smith, Dick Young, and Peter Gammons; and the essays of Roger Angell.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Among the celebrated nonfiction books in the field are Lawrence S.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Ritter's *The Glory of Their Times*, Roger Kahn's *The Boys of Summer*, and Michael Lewis's *Moneyball*.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] The 1970 publication of major league pitcher Jim Bouton's tell-all chronicle *Ball Four* is considered a turning point in the reporting of professional sports.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Baseball has also inspired the creation of new cultural forms.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Baseball cards were introduced in the late 19th century as trade cards.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] A typical example featured an image of a baseball player on one side and advertising for a business on the other.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] In the early 1900s they were produced widely as promotional items by tobacco and confectionery companies.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] The 1930s saw the popularization of the modern style of baseball card, with a player photograph accompanied on the rear by statistics and biographical data.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Baseball cards—many of which are now prized collectibles—are the source of the much broader trading card industry, involving similar products for different sports and non-sports-related fields.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Modern fantasy sports began in 1980 with the invention of Rotisserie League Baseball by New York writer Daniel Okrent and several friends.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Participants in a Rotisserie league draft notional teams from the list of active MLB players and play out an entire imaginary season with game outcomes based on the players' latest real-world statistics.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Rotisserie-style play quickly became a phenomenon.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Now known more generically as fantasy baseball, it has inspired similar games based on an array of different sports.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] The field boomed with increasing Internet access and new fantasy sports-related websites.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] By 2008, 29.9 million people in the United States and Canada were playing fantasy sports, spending $800 million on the hobby.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] The burgeoning popularity of fantasy baseball is also credited with the increasing attention paid to sabermetrics—first among fans, only later among baseball professionals.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Informal variations of baseball have popped up over time, with games like corkball reflecting local traditions and allowing the game to be played in diverse environments.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Two variations of baseball, softball and Baseball5, are internationally governed alongside baseball by the World Baseball Softball Confederation.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] American professional baseball teams toured Britain in 1874 and 1889, and had a great effect on similar sports in Britain.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] In Wales and Merseyside, a strong community game had already developed with skills and plays more in keeping with the American game and the Welsh began to informally adopt the name "baseball" (Pêl Fas), to reflect the American style.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] By the 1890s, calls were made to follow the success of other working class sports (like Rugby in Wales and Soccer in Merseyside) and adopt a distinct set of rules and bureaucracy.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] During the 1892 season rules for the game of "baseball" were agreed and the game was officially codified.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] Finnish baseball, also known as pesäpallo, is a combination of traditional ball-batting team games and North American baseball, invented by Lauri "Tahko" Pihkala in the 1920s.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] The basic idea of pesäpallo is similar to that of baseball: the offense tries to score by hitting the ball successfully and running through the bases, while the defense tries to put the batter and runners out.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] One of the most important differences between pesäpallo and baseball is that the ball is pitched vertically, which makes hitting the ball, as well as controlling the power and direction of the hit, much easier.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-p02] This gives the offensive game more variety, speed, and tactical aspects compared to baseball.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-reference] Founder Sean Forman began developing the website while working on his Ph.D. dissertation in applied math and computational science at the University of Iowa.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-reference] While writing his dissertation, he had also been writing articles on and blogging about sabermetrics.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-reference] Forman's database was originally built from the *Total Baseball* series of baseball encyclopedias.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-reference] The website went online in April 2000, after first being launched in February 2000 as part of the website for the *Big Bad Baseball Annual*.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-reference] It was originally built as a web interface to the Lahman Baseball Database, though it now employs a variety of data sources.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-reference] In 2004, Forman founded Sports Reference.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-reference] Sports Reference is a website that came out of the Baseball Reference website.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-reference] The company was incorporated as Sports Reference, LLC in 2007.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-reference] In 2006, Forman left his job as a math professor at Saint Joseph's University to focus on Baseball Reference full-time.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-reference] In February 2009, Fantasy Sports Ventures took a minority stake in Sports Reference, for a "low seven-figure sum".
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-reference] In late April 2021, the site changed a number of identifying names, "discontinuing the use of nicknames that are racially or ethnically influenced" and "names based upon a player's disability", such as Chief Bender and Dummy Hoy, who are now listed as Charles Bender and Billy Hoy, respectively.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-reference] To compare ballplayers to one-another it offers "Black Ink" and "Gray Ink" tests, which tally a player's dominance and overall productivity against his peers.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-reference] In 2012, it began to offer Jay Jaffe's Jaffe Wins Above Replacement Score (JAWS) statistic for comparing players of different eras against each other by weighing their performance in the prime as well as their entire career.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference began including its version of Wins Above Replacement (WAR) in 2010.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-reference] Its version determining a player's value differs slightly from other baseball statistics websites, including FanGraphs and Baseball Prospectus.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference has its own baseball encyclopedia, a wiki called "Baseball Reference Bullpen", which can be edited by anyone and is modeled after Wikipedia.
[src:charlie-knepper/baseball-reference] As of November 2025, the Bullpen contains more than 123,000 articles.
[src:charlie-knepper/charlie-knepper] Knepper spent just one season in the majors, pitching for the 1899 Cleveland Spiders, a notoriously futile team that set a major league record by losing 134 games.
[src:charlie-knepper/charlie-knepper] Knepper was one of that team's primary starting pitchers, and he tied Jim Hughey for the team lead with four wins.
[src:charlie-knepper/charlie-knepper] He also ranked among the National League's leaders in several undesirable pitching categories, including home runs allowed (second, with 11), losses (fourth, with 22), earned runs allowed (seventh, with 141), and wild pitches (tenth, with eight).
[src:charlie-knepper/charlie-knepper] During a game on June 24, 1899, he hit a double, and the next day *The Plain Dealer's* game recap stated that "a hay wagon drawn by lame horses could have reached third, but Knepper is no hay wagon and had no lame horses to assist him".
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The **Cleveland Spiders** were an American professional baseball team based in Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The team competed at the major league level from 1887 to 1899, first for two seasons as a member of the now-defunct American Association (AA), followed by eleven seasons in the National League (NL).
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Early names for the team included the **Forest Citys** and **Blues**.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The name Spiders itself emerged early in the team's inaugural NL season of 1889, owing to new black-and-gray uniforms and the skinny, long-limbed look of many players (thereby resembling the spider).
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] National League Park served as the team's home for its first four seasons until the opening of League Park in 1891.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Amid seven straight winning seasons under manager Patsy Tebeau, the team finished second in the National League three times – in 1892, 1895, and 1896.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] While the Spiders never won the National League pennant, the club did win the 1895 Temple Cup, a two-team league championship playoff predating the World Series.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders beat that year's pennant winner, the Baltimore Orioles (unrelated to the modern franchise), four games to one in a best-of-seven game series.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Six Spiders players were later inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame, including left fielder Jesse Burkett and pitcher Cy Young.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] In 1899, owners Frank and Stanley Robison purchased a second team – the bankrupt St.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Louis NL franchise – and sent all of the Spiders' top talent to that club, including future Hall-of-Famers Young, Burkett, and Bobby Wallace.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The resulting Spiders roster finished the 1899 season 20–134, a record which remains the worst for a single season in major league history.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders were subsequently one of four teams contracted by the National League that year.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Partly in response to the Robison brothers' actions – which effectively ended the Spiders franchise – the practice of "syndicate ownership" was later banned.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Spiders outfielder Louis Sockalexis played for the team during its final three seasons and is often credited as the first Native American to play major league baseball.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The Cleveland Guardians, major league successor to the Spiders in Cleveland, have long cited Sockalexis as the inspiration for their controversial former team name – "Indians" – though that claim is disputed.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders were the third professional baseball franchise based in Cleveland.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The first team, Forest City, which played from 1870 through 1872, was initially an independent team before joining the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players for two seasons before disbanding.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] They were followed in 1879 by the city's first National League team, the Cleveland Blues, which folded after the 1884 season.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] After the 1886 season, the Pittsburgh Alleghenys left the American Association (AA) to join the National League.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The AA, then considered a major league, chose the Cleveland group headed by Frank Robison as an expansion team to begin play in 1887 over proposals from Kansas City and Detroit.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Later, Robison's brother Stanley was added to the ownership group.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Initially, the team was known as the Forest Citys, drawing on the city's nickname and the nickname that had been used on the city's two previous professional baseball teams.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The nickname Blues was also used again in reference to the team uniforms.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The Forest Citys were a weak team in their early years.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] In 1889, they moved to the National League and became known as the Spiders, reportedly after comments from a team executive assessing the players.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Brunell, this team executive who also doubled as sportswriter for *The Plain Dealer*, noted the combination of the team's new black-and-gray uniforms together with the sight of several skinny, long-limbed players.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] He joked the team should be called "Spiders", and the name stuck.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The team started to improve in 1891, largely due to the signing of future Baseball Hall of Fame pitcher Cy Young.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders had their first taste of success in 1892 when they finished 93–56 overall; winning the second half by three games over Boston with a 53–23 record.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Other than standout second baseman Cupid Childs, the Spiders had an unremarkable offense.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Their success in 1892 was built on pitching strength; Cy Young was the NL's most dominant hurler, and 22-year-old George Cuppy had an outstanding rookie year.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Following the season, a "World's Championship Series" exhibition was played between Cleveland and the first-half winner Boston Beaneaters, but the Spiders could only muster one tie in six games.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] In 1895, the Spiders again finished second, this time to the equally rough-and-tumble Baltimore Orioles.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Young again led the league in wins, and speedy left fielder Jesse Burkett won the batting title with a .409 average.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders won the Temple Cup, an 1890s postseason series between the first- and second-place teams in the NL.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Amid fan rowdyism and garbage-throwing, the Spiders won four of five games against Baltimore, including two wins for Cy Young.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The 1895 championship was the high-water mark for the franchise.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The following season, Baltimore and Cleveland again finished first and second in the NL, but in the battle for the 1896 Temple Cup, the second-place Spiders were swept in four games.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] In 1897, despite a winning record, the franchise finished fifth, a season highlighted by Young throwing the first of three career no-hitters on September 18.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders again finished fifth in 1898.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] In 1899, the Spiders' owners, the Robison brothers, bought the St.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Louis Browns out of bankruptcy and changed their name to the Perfectos.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] However, they kept the Spiders as well—a blatant conflict of interest.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Believing the Perfectos would draw greater attendance in more densely populated St.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Louis, the Robisons transferred most of the Cleveland stars, including future Baseball Hall of Famers Cy Young, Jesse Burkett, and Bobby Wallace, to St.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] They also shifted a large number of Cleveland home games to the road (for instance, the original Opening Day game was shifted to St.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] With a decimated roster, the Spiders made a wretched showing.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] They finished with a dismal win-loss record of 20–134 (.130), the worst in MLB history, 84 games behind the pennant-winning Brooklyn Superbas and 35 games behind the next-to-last (11th) place Washington Senators.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Their batting records were the worst in the league in runs, hits, doubles, triples, home runs, walks, stolen bases, on-base percentage, and slugging percentage.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The Robisons announced after buying the Perfectos that they intended to run the Spiders as a "sideshow", and Cleveland fans apparently took them at their word.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders' first 16 home games drew a total of 3,179 fans, or an average of 199 fans per game.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Due to these meager attendance figures, the other 11 NL teams refused to come to League Park, as their cut of the revenue from ticket sales did not even begin to cover their hotel and travel expenses.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The Spiders were thus forced to play 85 of their remaining 93 games on the road.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Counting the large number of home games that had been shifted to the road earlier in the season, they only played 42 home games during the season, including only eight after July 1, and finished 9–33 (.214) at home and 11–101 (.098) on the road.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Only 6,088 fans paid to attend Spiders home games in 1899, for a pitiful average of a mere 145 spectators per game in 9,000-seat League Park.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The 101 road losses is a major-league record that will never be threatened, as current scheduling practices have teams play a maximum of 81 away games.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The team's longest winning streak of the season was two games, which they accomplished once: on May 20–21.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Spiders opponents scored ten or more runs 49 times in 154 games.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Pitchers Jim Hughey (4–30) and Charlie Knepper (4–22) tied for the team lead in wins.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The 1962 New York Mets, 40–120 (.250), and the 2024 Chicago White Sox, 41–121 (.253), own the modern records in their respective leagues for the most losses, and thus draw frequent comparisons to the 1899 Spiders for futility.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The Robisons' decision to effectively reduce the Spiders to minor league status, along with other intra-league raiding such as that conducted by the Dodgers and to a lesser extent the Pittsburgh Pirates, unwittingly helped pave the way to the National League's loss of its major league monopoly.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The 12th-place Spiders were one of four teams contracted out of the National League at the end of the 1899 season (the others were the 11th-place Senators, the ninth-place Louisville Colonels and the bankrupt fourth-place Baltimore Orioles).
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The 1899 fiasco played a role in the major leagues passing a rule which barred one person from owning controlling interest in two clubs.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The Robisons sold the assets of the Spiders team to Charles Somers and John Kilfoyle in 1900.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] In 1900, the then-minor American League (previously the Western League) moved the Grand Rapids (baseball) team in to take the Spiders' place, and called the Cleveland Lake Shores.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] In 1901, after the American League declared major league status, the team was called the Cleveland Blues, eventually the Cleveland Indians, and now the Cleveland Guardians.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The Cleveland Guardians have long claimed Spiders outfielder Louis Sockalexis as the inspiration for their controversial former team name – "Indians" – in use from 1915 to 2021.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] Sockalexis played three seasons for the Cleveland Spiders, from 1897 to 1899, and is often credited as the first Native American to play professional baseball at the major league level.
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] During his time with the Spiders, the press often referred to the team as the Indians or "Tebeau's Indians".
[src:charlie-knepper/cleveland-spiders] The Cleveland Guardians claim has been disputed, however, including in a 2012 *Cleveland Scene* essay titled "The Curse of Chief Wahoo", which argues the organization cited Sockalexis in part to justify use of the "Indians" name.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] In baseball statistics, **earned run average** (**ERA**) is the average of earned runs allowed by a pitcher per nine innings pitched (i.e. the traditional length of a game).
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] It is determined by dividing the number of earned runs allowed by the number of innings pitched and multiplying by nine.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] Runs resulting from passed balls, defensive errors (including pitchers' defensive errors), and runners placed on base at the start of extra innings are recorded as unearned runs and omitted from ERA calculations.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] Henry Chadwick is credited with devising the statistic, which caught on as a measure of pitching effectiveness after relief pitching came into vogue in the 1900s.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] Prior to 1900 and for many years afterward, pitchers were routinely expected to pitch a complete game, and their win–loss record was considered sufficient in determining their effectiveness.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] After pitchers like James Otis Crandall and Charley Hall made names for themselves as relief specialists, gauging a pitcher's effectiveness became more difficult using the traditional method of tabulating wins and losses.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] Some criterion was needed to capture the apportionment of earned-run responsibility for a pitcher in games that saw contributions from other pitchers for the same team.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] Since pitchers have primary responsibility for getting opposing batters out, they must assume responsibility when a batter they do not retire at the plate moves to base, and eventually reaches home, scoring a run.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] A pitcher is assessed an **earned run** for each run scored by a batter (or the batter's pinch-runner) who reaches base while batting against that pitcher.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] The National League first tabulated official earned run average statistics in 1912 (the outcome was called "Heydler's statistic" for a while, after then-NL secretary John Heydler), and the American League later accepted this standard and began compiling ERA statistics.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] Baseball encyclopedias will often display ERAs for earlier years, but these were computed retroactively.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] Negro league pitchers are often rated by *RA*, or total runs allowed, since the statistics available for Negro league games did not always distinguish between earned and unearned runs.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] As with batting average, the definition of a good ERA varies from year to year.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] During the dead-ball era of the 1900s and 1910s, an ERA below 2.00 (two earned runs allowed per nine innings) was considered good.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] In the late 1920s and through the 1930s, when conditions of the game changed in a way that strongly favored hitters, a good ERA was below 4.00; only the highest caliber pitchers, for example Dazzy Vance or Lefty Grove, would consistently post an ERA under 3.00 during these years.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] In the 1960s, sub-2.00 ERAs returned as other influences, such as ballparks with different dimensions, were introduced.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] Starting with the 2019 season, an ERA under 4.00 is again considered good.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] The single-season record for the lowest ERA is held by Dutch Leonard, who in 1914 had an earned run average of 0.96, pitching 224.2 innings with a win–loss record of 19–5.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] The all-time record for the lowest single season earned run average by a pitcher pitching 300 or more innings is 1.12, set by Bob Gibson in 1968.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] The record for the lowest career earned run average is 1.82, held by Ed Walsh, who played from 1904 through 1917.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] Some players may be listed with infinite ERAs.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] This can happen if a pitcher allows one or more earned runs without retiring a batter.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] Several players have registered an infinite ERA for their limited pitching careers in MLB, usually a single appearance.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] Examples include Bill Ford with the Boston Bees in 1936 and Fred Bruckbauer with the Minnesota Twins in 1961.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] Outfielder Vic Davalillo made two pitching appearances with St.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] Louis Cardinals in 1969 and failed to record an out while facing four batters and allowing one run, leaving him with an infinite ERA as a major-league pitcher.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] (This comes from attempting to divide any non-zero number by zero).
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] An undefined ERA occasionally occurs at the beginning of a baseball season when a pitcher has yet to appear in any games.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] It is sometimes incorrectly displayed as zero or as the lowest-ranking ERA.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] At times it can be misleading to judge relief pitchers solely on ERA, because they are charged only for runs scored by batters who reached base while batting against them.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] Thus, if a relief pitcher enters the game while his team is leading by 1 run, with 2 outs and the bases loaded, and then gives up a single which scores 2 runs, he is not charged with those runs.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] If he retires the next batter (and pitches no more innings), his ERA for that game will be 0.00 despite having surrendered the lead.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] (He is recorded with a blown save if those runs tied the game or affected a lead change.) Starting pitchers operate under the same rules, but are not called upon to start pitching with runners already on base.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] In addition, relief pitchers know beforehand that they will only be pitching for a relatively short while, allowing them to exert themselves more for each pitch, unlike starters who typically need to conserve their energy over the course of a game in case they are asked to pitch 7 or more innings.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] The reliever's freedom to use their maximum energy for a few innings, or even for just a few batters, helps them keep their ERAs down.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] ERA, taken by itself, can also be misleading when trying to objectively judge starting pitchers, though not to the extent seen with relief pitchers.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] The advent of the designated hitter rule in the American League in 1973 made the pitching environment significantly different.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] Starting in 1997, when teams began playing teams from the other league during the regular season, the DH rule was in effect only when such interleague games are played in an American League park; this was rendered moot after the National League permanently adopted the DH in 2022.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] This difference between the leagues (the DH) also affected relievers, but not to the same degree.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] This is because National League relievers actually pitched to pitchers less often than NL starters did for a number of reasons, mainly because relievers are usually active in later innings when the double switch was available and/or pinch hitters tended to be used in the pitcher's batting spot.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] ERA is also affected somewhat by the ballpark where a pitcher's team plays half its games, as well as the tendency of hometown official scorers to assign errors instead of base hits in plays that could be either.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] As an extreme example, pitchers for the Colorado Rockies have historically faced many problems, all damaging to their ERAs.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] The combination of high altitude (5,280 ft or 1,610 m) and a semi-arid climate in Denver causes fly balls to travel up to 10% further than at sea level.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] Denver's altitude and low humidity also diminish the ability of pitchers to throw effective breaking balls, due to both reduced air resistance and difficulty in gripping dry baseballs.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] These conditions have been countered to some extent since 2002 by the team's use of humidors to store baseballs before games.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] These difficult circumstances for Rockies pitchers may not adversely affect their win–loss records, since opposing pitchers must deal with the same problems.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] Indeed, hometown hurlers have some advantage in any given game since they are physically acclimated to the altitude and often develop techniques to mitigate the challenges of this ballpark.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] Still, conditions there tend to inflate Rockies' ERAs relative to the rest of the league.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] In modern baseball, sabermetrics uses several defense independent pitching statistics (DIPS) including a Defense-Independent ERA in an attempt to measure a pitcher's ability regardless of factors outside his control.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] For example, this is the premise of Nate Silver's forecasts of ERAs using his PECOTA system.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] Silver also developed a "quick" earned run average (QuikERA or QERA) to calculate an ERA from peripheral statistics including strikeouts, walks, and groundball percentage.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] Unlike peripheral ERA or PERA, it does not take into account park effects.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] Another statistic derived from ERA is Adjusted ERA, also called ERA+, which adjusts a pitcher's ERA to a scale where 100 is average for the league and takes into account the various dimensions and other factors of each ballpark.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] In baseball statistics, **runs per nine innings** (denoted by **R/9** or **RA9**) is a measure of a pitcher's effectiveness in preventing runs; calculated as: (9 × runs allowed) / (innings pitched).
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] In this way, it is different from the ERA in that all runs, rather than only earned runs, are included.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run-average] This is a list of the lowest ERAs among pitchers that played their entire careers after 1920 (minimum 1,500 innings pitched, starting pitcher).
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] In baseball, an **earned run** is any run that was fully enabled by the offensive team's production in the face of competent play from the defensive team.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] Conversely, an **unearned run** is a run that would not have been scored without the aid of an error or a passed ball committed by the defense; it is "unearned" in that it was, in a sense, "given away" by the defensive team.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] Earned and unearned runs count equally toward the game score; the difference is purely statistical.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] Thus, in effect, the pitcher is held personally accountable for earned runs, while the responsibility for unearned runs is shared with the rest of the team.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] To determine whether a run is earned, the official scorer must reconstruct the inning as it would have occurred without errors or passed balls.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] If no errors and no passed balls occur during the inning, all runs scored are automatically earned (assigned responsible to the pitcher(s) who allowed each runner to reach base).
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] Also, in some cases, an error can be rendered harmless as the inning progresses.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] For example, a runner on first base advances to second on a passed ball and the next batter walks.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] Since the runner would now have been at second anyway, the passed ball no longer has any effect on the earned/unearned calculation.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] On the other hand, a batter/runner may make his entire circuit around the bases without the aid of an error, yet the run would be counted as unearned if an error prevented the third out from being made before he crossed the plate to score.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] An error made by the pitcher in fielding at his position is counted the same as an error by any other player.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] While the inning is still being played, the second and the second-last scenario can cause a temporary situation where a run has already scored, but its earned/unearned status is not yet certain.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] Under the last circumstance, for example, with two outs, a runner on third base scores on a passed ball.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] For the time being, the run is unearned since the runner *should* still be at third.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] If the batter strikes out to end the inning, it will stay that way.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] If the batter gets a base hit, which would have scored the runner anyway, the run now becomes earned.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] Under the second circumstance, if there are runners on base and a batter hits a foul fly ball that is dropped, and then bats in the runners on base through a base hit (including a home run), the runs are unearned for the time being, as the runners should not have advanced.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] If the results of the remaining at-bats in the inning would not have scored the runners, the runs remain unearned.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] However, if results of subsequent at-bats would have scored the runs anyway, the runs would count as earned, unless they only would have scored as a result of a subsequent error or passed ball.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] If a run is scored by a pinch-runner who replaces a baserunner who represents an unearned run, or by a pinch-hitter who continues the turn at bat of a batter who would be out except for an error, the run remains unearned, regardless of the substitution.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] When pitchers are changed in the middle of an inning, and one or more errors have already occurred, it is possible to have a run charged as earned against a specific pitcher, but unearned to the team.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] The simplest example is when the defensive team records two outs and makes an error on a play that would have been the third out.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] A new pitcher comes into the game, and the next batter hits a home run.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] The runner who reached on the error comes around to score, and his run is unearned to both the prior pitcher and the team.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] However, the run scored by the batter is counted as earned against the relief pitcher, but unearned to the team (since there should have already been three outs).
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] Had the team not switched pitchers, neither run would be counted as an earned run because that pitcher should have already been out of that inning.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] A pitcher who is relieved mid-inning may be charged with earned runs equal to the number of batters who reached base while he was pitching, even if the specific batters he faced do not score.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] The batters he put on base may be erased by fielder's choice plays after he has been relieved by another pitcher, but if earned runs are scored in the inning the original pitcher is liable for as many earned runs as the number of batters he put on base.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] Greene walked the next batter to load the bases.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] threw home to force out the runner on third in a fielder's choice, so the bases remained loaded with one out.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] Greene struck out the next batter for the second out.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] then hit a single that scored the runners from second and third (only one of whom was put on base by Verlander), and the runner from first was thrown out at the plate to end the inning.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] Since Verlander allowed two batters to reach base, he was charged with two earned runs, even though only one of the two specific batters he faced actually scored.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] When a pitching change occurs, the new pitcher is said to "inherit" any runners that are on base at the time, and if they later score, those runs are charged (earned or unearned) to the prior pitcher.
[src:charlie-knepper/earned-run] Most box scores now list inherited runners, and the number that scored, as a statistic for the relief pitcher.
